<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1866,2027]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1437,152,279]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="291" pageId="1" pageNumber="290">
The male is not described for 
<emphasis box="[513,599,1866,1889]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="290">pulcher.</emphasis>
In the male of 
<taxonomicName box="[758,863,1866,1889]" class="Insecta" family="Aeolothripidae" genus="Aeolothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="290" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eremicola">
<emphasis box="[758,863,1866,1889]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="290">eremicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the tergites are without tubercles and tergite IX lacks claspers and stout setae. In contrast, both 
<emphasis box="[595,688,1900,1923]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="290">insularis</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[740,860,1900,1923]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="290">melaleucus</emphasis>
have paired tubercles on tergites IV–V, and tergite IX has non-bifurcate claspers. Of the remaining two species in the group, the male of 
<taxonomicName box="[1081,1191,1935,1958]" class="Insecta" family="Aeolothripidae" genus="Aeolothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="290" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eremicola">
<emphasis box="[1081,1191,1935,1958]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="290">eremicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished from 
<emphasis box="[151,244,1970,1993]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="290">wittmeri</emphasis>
by the lack of a pair of stout setae on the hind margin of tergite IX (see zur Strassen 
<number box="[1210,1268,1970,1993]" pageId="1" pageNumber="290" value="2003.0">2003</number>
, page 
<number box="[1341,1373,1970,1993]" pageId="1" pageNumber="290" value="55.0">55</number>
). The abdomen is similar in structure to 
<emphasis box="[521,629,2004,2027]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="290">versicolor</emphasis>
, but these species differ in the pigmentation of the fore wings as indicated above. Moreover, antennal segment III in 
<taxonomicName box="[612,720,152,175]" class="Insecta" family="Aeolothripidae" genus="Aeolothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="291" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eremicola">
<emphasis box="[612,720,152,175]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="291">eremicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is brown in the apical two-thirds, but only the apical one third in 
<emphasis box="[151,258,186,209]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="291">versicolor</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,152,279]" pageId="2" pageNumber="291">The small number of collected specimens on various plants suggests this species is a predator, but further investigations with a good series of specimens are needed.</paragraph>
